				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${k}_{{SP}}$$\end{document} and kTP\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${k}_{{TP}}$$\end{document} as 2 × 10−11 cm3 s−1 and 9.1 × 10−13 cm3 s−1, respectively. Interestingly, both the SPA and TPA rates from OLEDs were slightly higher than the value obtained from dual excitation method in HODs. This hints toward the existence of additional loss mechanisms in OLEDs that may potentially also induce EQE roll-off, such as optical loss mechanisms32,33 and joule heating34.Fig. 3Device characteristics of mCP:4CzIPN OLEDs.
a Current density−voltage−luminance plot. b EQE−current density plot. The solid line represents fit obtained from Eqs. (3)–(6).

